</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called a <html:em><html:strong>set</html:strong></html:em> when for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y:A]]></fr:tex> the identification type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001I.xml" title="Proposition" addr="forest://erct/erct-001I" type="local">proposition</fr:link>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>The notions of <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001H.xml" title="Contractible type" addr="forest://erct/erct-001H" type="local">contractible</fr:link> and <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001I.xml" title="Proposition" addr="forest://erct/erct-001I" type="local">propositional</fr:link> types generate an infinite hierarchy of <html:em>truncation levels</html:em> expressing the point after which higher identifications become trivial.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
